## Pavé Band (No Halo): The Sweet Spot

The pavé band — a solitaire-style setting where the shank (band) is encrusted with small diamonds, but there is no halo around the center stone — is the design I recommend to most buyers who want more sparkle than a plain solitaire without the Clarity Laundering Effect of a halo.

The logic: the pavé band adds sparkle and visual richness to the ring without competing with or obscuring the center stone. The center diamond remains the clear focal point. From above, the diamond's full face-up performance is visible. From the side, the pavé band adds continuous sparkle along the shank.

Cost differential over plain solitaire: $300–$600 for a half-pavé band (diamonds on top half of shank), $500–$900 for a full-pavé band (diamonds continuing all the way around).

For a $3,200 center stone ([G-VS1 Excellent round →](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28915027?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)) — see the [1 carat round diamond price guide](/1-carat-round-diamond-price) for every budget tier — plus a half-pavé solitaire setting at $700–$900, total ring cost runs $3,900–$4,100 — excellent value for the result.

For a $3,760 center stone ([G-VVS2 Excellent round →](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27622805?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)) plus a half-pavé setting, total ring cost runs approximately $4,460–$4,660.

