## Metal Choice: Platinum vs White Gold vs Yellow Gold

This is a decision with real trade-offs and no universal right answer. Here is what each metal actually delivers:

### Platinum

- Naturally white and does not fade or yellow over time
- More dense and durable than gold — resists scratching better
- Develops a patina (slight matte finish) over years of wear; can be polished back to high shine
- Setting cost: 30–50% more than 14k white gold for the same design
- Right for: buyers who want zero maintenance, maximum durability, permanent whiteness, or whose partner has a platinum preference

### 14k White Gold

- Less expensive than platinum (typically $200–$600 less for the same setting)
- White appearance achieved with rhodium plating — a thin coating that wears off over 12–24 months of daily wear, exposing the yellow gold alloy beneath
- Requires rhodium re-plating every 1–2 years at a jeweler (typically $50–$100)
- Slightly harder than platinum (less prone to surface scratching), but less durable in deep impacts
- Right for: buyers who want the white metal look at lower cost and are willing to do occasional maintenance

### 14k Yellow Gold

- Flattering for G–H color diamonds — the gold's warmth is indistinguishable from color in the stone, meaning a slightly lower color grade works well in yellow gold without showing yellow tint
- No plating required — maintains its color permanently
- Slightly more traditional aesthetic — experiencing a genuine style resurgence in {{year}}
- Right for: buyers who prefer warm metal tones, buyers with H–I color diamonds (the gold masks any trace of warmth), buyers who want a maintenance-free metal without platinum cost

---

## The Hidden Halo Trap

The hidden halo — a row of small diamonds set underneath the center stone, visible from the side but not the top — has become extremely popular. Before paying for it, understand what you are buying.

A hidden halo is visible only when:
- The ring is tilted and viewed from the side
- The viewer is positioned at girdle height or below
- The lighting conditions allow the small diamonds to be seen

From the standard viewing angle — looking at the ring on a hand — a hidden halo is not visible. You are paying $400–$800 more for sparkle that appears only in specific viewing conditions.

This is not to say hidden halos are worthless. When the ring is viewed from the side — which does happen regularly in social settings — the hidden halo creates a surprising, distinctive sparkle effect that many people find genuinely beautiful. If that side-view aesthetic is important to your partner, the hidden halo is a legitimate purchase.

If the purchase rationale is "more sparkle on the ring overall," a half-pavé band delivers continuous visible sparkle for approximately the same cost and is visible from the top-down angle most people use.

